    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">New University Club, | S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. James’s Street. S.W.</hi></placeName>
                    <salute>Dear Father</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Klein says the water ought to be changed every day<ref target="#foot.f1"/>   I should think you might draw if off with a syphon, which Jim could rig up with glass tubing &amp; indiarubber ditto— I found I could pour off a good deal of water by stretching a bit of gauze over the lip of the basin.</p> 
<figure rend="blockCentred width20"> 
    <graphic url="../images/DCP-LETT-8713F.svg"/>
</figure> 
<p rend="left">I left a bit I used on the fern heap in Deadman’s corner; but I should think the syphon wd be best— Please tell G the Revalenta shop is shut today.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Klein says his discovery about toads’ ova does <hi rend="underline">not</hi> bear on pangenesis.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I don’t know why he said it was good for you.</p>
<p>Yr affec | Frank Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2716.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edward Emanuel Klein</ref> was a bacteriologist and histologist. The experiment has not been identified. Jim was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1226.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Horace Darwin’s</ref> nickname.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Francis probably refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Howard Darwin</ref>. Revalenta was a mixture of lentil and barley meal, sold as a health food (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3430.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hassall 1855</ref>, pp. 237–50).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The discovery has not been identified. For CD’s hypothesis of pangenesis, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 2: 357–404.</note>
        </div>        
            
